passages.text: More developments in global navaorders; raise PT to W140K

We raise our Dec- 26 PT from W130K to W140K, implying \(25\%\) upside to the current share price. We are seeing heightened visibility for the defense opportunities in both the US and non- US regions, which we believe is the key valuation re- rating factor for the Korean shipbuilding sector. In the US, while we are still waiting for potential changes or exceptions to the Byrnes- Tollefson Amendment, for which the Korean shipbuilders are lobbying aggressively in the US, we believe the recent US- Korea summit (link) indicates that Korea will have a strong role in rebuilding US Navy capabilities. In overseas ex- US, Hanwha Ocean has been selected as a finalist in the W60T Canada submarine contract (along with German TKMS), where Hanwha has a competitive edge in delivery time. The Canadian prime minister will also make a visit to Hanwha's Geojie shipyard in October. We see a huge TAM in the global navy market, which amounts to \(\) 199B\(as per our estimate (link to report), and we note that these orders would be margin accretive, given production domestically. We expect to see more developments around several naval orders in the short to mid term, including the Poland submarine order, ME orders for both surface ships and submarines, and Thailand frigate re- orders. We expect Hanwha Ocean's share price to be strongest in the near term with several order- related catalysts. With heightened visibility on naval orders, we raise our target price orderbook multiple to 0.87x (from 0.8x) and raise our PT to W140K. Reiterate OW.

Global navy opportunity: Per our assumptions, the global ex- US TAM stands at \(\) 199B\(for Korea shipbuilders. Hanwha Ocean has an edge in non- nuclear submarine, for which the TAM stands at\) \ \(75B\) mostly coming from the ASEAN and Americas regions. The company guides 2030 navy related sales at W5T, which we consider too conservative - we believe the company can generate c. W12T in navy sales (US W3T, global ex- US W6T, domestic W3T) and OP of W1.3T by 2030.

Order pipeline: Hanwha Ocean has been shortlisted as one of the final two candidates for the Canadian Patrol Submarine Project, which is worth c. W60T. The Canadian prime minister will visit the Geojie shipyard in October, during which we could see more development around the order. Other than the Canada order, we are also waiting for: 1) Poland submarine contract worth W8T, which should come out by year- end or early 2026 - better technology, price and delivery vs. European competitors and signing of MOU with local shipyard gives us confidence for an order win; 2) ME order for 5 units of surface ships, and 4 units of submarines with orders likely granted in 2026- 2027; 3) Thailand Trigate order worth c. W1.3T - second batch of orders for Hanwha Ocean, with orders likely granted in early 2026.

We think the biggest catalyst for the sector should come from rising defense opportunities in both US and non- US regions, which would more than extend the current upcycle the Korean shipbuilders are enjoying - easing peak- out concerns on slowing global newbuild orders in 2025 and in turn the 2028 and beyond earnings outlook. We believe the company is in the lead to win the first naval ship order from the US given: 1) strong commitment shown through the Philly shipyard acquisition, 2) well established track record via 2 US Navy MRO contracts, 3) Hanwha Group's efforts to penetrate the US market with ammunition and howitzers. Hanwha Ocean also has a strong non- US defense pipeline worth c. \(\) 50B\(including Poland/ Canada submarine orders and Thailand frigate order.
We are OW on the stock with a Dec- 26 PT of W140k, based on a 0.87x price to orderbook multiple, applying a premium to the defense business.

Hanwha Ocean (Overweight; Price Target: W140,000)

We think the biggest catalyst for the sector should come from rising defense opportunities in both US and non- US regions, which would more than extend the current upcycle the Korean shipbuilders are enjoying - easing peak- out concerns on slowing global newbuild orders in 2025 and in turn the 2028 and beyond earnings outlook. We believe the company is in the lead to win the first naval ship order from the US given: 1) strong commitment shown through the Philly shipyard acquisition, 2) well established track record via 2 US Navy MRO contracts, 3) Hanwha Group's efforts to penetrate the US market with ammunition and howitzers. Hanwha Ocean also has a strong non- US defense pipeline worth c. \(\) 50\(B, including Poland/Canada submarine orders and Thailand frigate order.
We are OW on the stock with a Dec- 26 PT of W140k, based on a \(0.87x\) price to orderbook multiple, applying a premium to the defense business.
